'''James Robert "Jim" Johnson''' (born June 27, 1983) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[relief pitcher]] for the [[Oakland Athletics]] of [[Major League Baseball]]. 

==Early life==
Johnson was born in [[Johnson City, New York]]. He was raised in [[Endicott, New York]] and graduated from [[Union Endicott High School]] in 2001.

==Baseball career==
===Baltimore Orioles===
The [[Baltimore Orioles]] drafted Johnson in the fifth round of the [[2001 MLB Draft]].

He began the [[2008 Major League Baseball season|2008]] season in the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Norfolk Tides]] [[Starting pitcher|starting rotation]], but was called up to the Orioles on April 12th. Pitching middle and late [[Relief pitcher|relief]], he ran up 18 consecutive scoreless innings before giving up a 10th inning run to [[2008 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland]] on May 5th.<ref name="baltimoresun.com">[http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/baseball/bal-orioles807,0,1801755.story Topic Galleries]. ''Baltimore Sun''. Retrieved on 2012-04-09.</ref>

He became the interim [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] when [[George Sherrill]] went on the disabled list on August 19, 2008.<ref>[http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080819&content_id=3333336&vkey=pr_bal&fext=.jsp&c_id=bal Orioles place LHP George Sherrill on 15-day disabled list | orioles.com: Official Info]. Baltimore.orioles.mlb.com (2008-08-19). Retrieved on 2012-04-09.</ref> Johnson was given the closer role on July 30, 2009 when Sherrill was traded to the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]. In the [[2010 Major League Baseball season|2010 season]] he returned to a setup role. Late in the [[2011 Major League Baseball season|2011 season]], Johnson shared the closer role with [[Kevin Gregg]].{{cn|date=June 2012}}

[[File:JJ 2012.jpg|left|thumb|Jim Johnson pitches during a game vs. the Washington Nationals in 2012.]]
On January 16, 2012, Johnson signed a one-year deal worth $2.625 million, avoiding arbitration.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/#!/danconnollysun/status/159114864286117889 |title=Twitter |work=Baltimore Sun |first=Dan |last=Connolly |date=January 16, 2012}}</ref> He won the [[Major League Baseball Delivery Man Award|Delivery Man of the Month Award]] for May 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2012-06-03/sports/bal-orioles-closer-jim-johnson-named-mlb-delivery-man-of-the-month-for-may-20120603_1_orioles-closer-jim-johnson-mlb-delivery-man-era|title=Orioles closer Jim Johnson named MLB Delivery Man of the Month for May|date=June 3, 2012|first=Eduardo A.|last=Encina|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=June 8, 2012}}</ref> On July 1, 2012, Johnson was one of three Orioles selected to play in the [[2012 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2012 All Star Game]].<ref>[http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120701&content_id=34268138&vkey=news_bal&c_id=bal "Orioles trio tabbed for AL All-Star squad", Ghiroli, Brittany, Sunday, July 1, 2012.]</ref>

On September 21, 2012 Johnson set the Orioles' all-time single season save record at 46, passing [[Randy Myers]]. Johnson recorded his 50th save of the season on September 30 after a win over the [[2012 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]]. With the win, Baltimore clinched a post-season berth and Johnson became the 10th pitcher in MLB history to record 50 saves or more.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_09_30_bosmlb_balmlb_1#gid=2012_09_30_bosmlb_balmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=bal|title=Orioles clinch first postseason berth since 1997|work=[[MLB.com]]|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media|date=30 September 2012|accessdate=September 2012|last=Ghiroli|first=Brittany}}</ref> He finished the season with 51 saves. He won the AL [[Rolaids Relief Man Award]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolads Relief Man Award|work=rolaidsreliefman.com|url=http://www.rolaidsreliefman.com/|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Bi9MCzlb|archivedate=Octobner 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Johnson had a mediocre postseason debut through four games in the [[2012 American League Division Series]] against the [[2012 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]. Johnson struggled in game one of the series at Camden Yards, entering in the 9th inning of a 2<U+2013>2 game and surrendered five runs (four earned) in only {{fraction|1|3}} of an inning. The Yankees won, 7<U+2013>2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_10_07_nyamlb_balmlb_1&mode=box|title=MLB.com: Gameday|date=October 7, 2012|work=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=8 October 2012}}</ref> He gained redemption in game two, pitching a perfect 9th inning to preserve a 3<U+2013>2 advantage, striking out [[Alex Rodriguez]] on a 3<U+2013>2 count to end the game. Johnson pitched again in game three in the Bronx and surrendered a game-tying home run to [[Ra<U+00FA>l Iba<U+00F1>ez]] with one out in the 9th inning. (Iba<U+00F1>ez would also win the game on a homer in the 12th. off of [[Brian Matusz]])<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/ibanez-hrs-o-shock-article-1.1180544|title=Raul Ibanez home runs in Yankees' win have Orioles in a state of shock after Game 3 collapse|last=Brennan|first=Sean|date=October 11, 2012|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref> Johnson earned a successful save in game four, working a scoreless 13th inning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/orioles/blog/bal-pedro-strop-jim-johnson-come-up-big-for-baltimore-orioles-20121012,0,2585522.story|title=Pedro Strop, Jim Johnson come up big for Baltimore Orioles|last=Connolly|first=Dan|date=October 12, 2012|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref>

===Oakland Athletics===
On December 2, 2013, Johnson was traded to the [[Oakland Athletics]] for infielder [[Jemile Weeks]] and a [[player to be named later]], identified as [[David Freitas]] on December 12.<ref>http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-12-12/sports/bal-orioles-acquire-freitas-to-complete-jim-johnson-deal-20131212_1_jim-johnson-trade-baseball-america-catcher</ref>

===Pitching style===
Johnson throws four pitches, leading with a hard [[sinker (baseball)|sinker]] averaging 95&nbsp;mph. His main off-speed pitch to right-handed hitters is a [[curveball]] averaging about 80&nbsp;mph. Against lefties, Johnson adds an upper-80s [[changeup]]. Lastly, he throws an occasional [[four-seam fastball]] in the mid 90s.<ref>{{cite web|title=PITCHf/x Player Card: Jim Johnson|url=http://brooksbaseball.net/player_cards/player_card.php?player=462382|publisher=Brooks Baseball|accessdate=10 July 2012}}</ref>

